About Section

Official Overview

Central Luzon: The Rice Granary of the Philippines

Region III is a vast fertile plain located north of Manila. It serves as the primary source of the country's rice supply, making it a critical pillar of national food security. Beyond its fields, it is a booming hub for Agri-Business and Digital Transformation.

Regional Center:
City of San Fernando, Pampanga

Land Area (km²): 22,015
The largest contiguous plain in the country.

Population: 12.99M
A vibrant community across 7 diverse provinces.

Digital Readiness: DGT
Driving modern ICT infrastructure in the region.

Palay Production: Top 1
Consistently leading the nation in grain harvest.

Provincial Odyssey

Aurora – Gateway to the Pacific Coast
Facing the vast Pacific Ocean, Aurora is a sanctuary where the rugged Sierra Madre mountains meet turquoise waters. Known as the Birthplace of Philippine Surfing in Baler, it also holds deep historical roots as the home of President Manuel L. Quezon and the site of the historic Siege of Baler.

Bataan – Land of Valor & Progress
A peninsula steeped in heroism, Bataan is home to the Shrine of Valor (Mount Samat) which honors the bravery of soldiers during WWII. Today, it has transformed into a major industrial powerhouse with its Freeport Area, while maintaining eco-tourism gems like the Las Casas Filipinas de Acuzar.

Bulacan – The Cradle of Noble Heroes
The historical heart of the Philippines, Bulacan is the site of the Malolos Congress and the iconic Barasoain Church. It is celebrated for craftsmanship in jewelry, pyrotechnics, leather, and rich culinary traditions and festivals like the Singkaban.

Nueva Ecija – The Rice Granary of the Philippines
Serving as the backbone of national food security, Nueva Ecija is the leading producer of agricultural staples. It is also home to Minalungao National Park and a hub for agri-tourism.

Pampanga – Culinary Capital of the Philippines
A world-class destination for gastronomy, known for Kapampangan flavors, Giant Lanterns, and as a gateway through Clark Freeport Zone and International Airport.

Tarlac – The Melting Pot of Central Luzon
A blend of Ilocano, Pangasinan, Pampango, and Tagalog cultures. Home to Monasterio de Tarlac and Mount Pinatubo.

Zambales – The Chrome & Surf Destination
Known for Anawangin Cove, San Felipe surfing, Subic Bay industry, and sweet mango production.

