Hero Section – Bataan

Bataan, Central Luzon

Province of Bataan

Nestled on a peninsula between the West Philippine Sea and Manila Bay, Bataan is a province of remarkable depth — where the echoes of World War II heroes meet the rustling of rice fields, coconut groves, and thriving coastal fishponds. A land that has endured, rebuilt, and flourished.

Our History
Scroll to discover

Agriculture

Fertile Harvests

From the lowland plains where rice and corn sway in the breeze, to the coastal fishponds teeming with milkfish and shrimp along Manila Bay, Bataan's agricultural landscape is as diverse as it is productive. Its farmers and fisherfolk are the quiet backbone of Central Luzon — feeding families and driving regional growth one harvest at a time.

Nature & Heritage

Nature & Heritage

Beyond its wartime legacy, Bataan is a province of breathtaking natural beauty. Bagac's unspoiled shores, the dense forests of Mount Natib, the crystal waters of Nagsasa Cove, and the solemn grandeur of Mount Samat's Shrine of Valor — together they paint a destination unlike any other in Central Luzon, where history, nature, and culture converge.

Tourist Spots

History of Bataan

The Story of Bataan
History of Bataan

From ancient Tagalog settlements to one of World War II's most defining chapters, Bataan's history is woven with courage, sacrifice, and resilience that continues to shape its identity today.

Pre-Colonial Bataan (Before 1571)

Long before Spanish colonization, Bataan was home to indigenous Tagalog and Aeta communities who thrived along its coastlines and dense forests. The Aetas — considered the first inhabitants of the Philippine archipelago — built their lives in Bataan's mountains, living off its rich natural resources.

Early coastal barangays engaged in trade with neighboring islands and mainland Asia, establishing Bataan as a minor but active node in the pre-colonial maritime trade network. The name "Bataan" is believed to derive from the Tagalog word bata, meaning "child," though some historians link it to a local chieftain's name.

Spanish Rule (1571 – 1898)

Spanish colonizers arrived in Bataan in the late 16th century, establishing missions and reorganizing communities into encomiendas. Catholic churches were built across the peninsula — many still stand today.

Bataan became strategically important due to its position guarding the entrance to Manila Bay. Coastal defenses and forts were constructed. Agriculture expanded, with coconut, tobacco, and rice as primary products.

By the 19th century, revolutionary sentiment grew. Bataan contributed fighters to Emilio Aguinaldo's revolutionary forces during the Philippine Revolution of 1896.

World War II – Battle of Bataan (January – April 1942)

After Japan attacked the Philippines on December 8, 1941, Filipino and American forces (USAFFE) retreated to Bataan.

For nearly four months, around 75,000 soldiers resisted Japanese forces under extreme conditions.

On April 9, 1942 (Araw ng Kagitingan), Bataan fell after Major General Edward King surrendered.

The Bataan Death March (April – May 1942)

Around 75,000 Filipino and American prisoners of war were forced to march over 100 kilometers from Mariveles to Camp O'Donnell in Capas, Tarlac.

They suffered abuse, starvation, dehydration, and disease. Thousands died (estimated 5,000–18,000).

This event is remembered as one of the worst war crimes of World War II.

Post-War to Present (1945 – Present)

After liberation in 1945, Bataan rebuilt its communities and economy.

Balanga became the capital in 1980.

The Bataan Economic Zone in Mariveles boosted industrial growth.

Today, Bataan is both an agricultural and industrial province with a growing tourism sector.

April 9 is observed as Araw ng Kagitingan at Mount Samat National Shrine (Dambana ng Kagitingan).

Culture of Bataan

Discover the culture of Bataan

Cultural Heritage of Bataan

Bataan’s culture blends historical heroism, Spanish-era heritage, and coastal beauty.

It is known for:

WWII Death March history
Mt. Samat National Shrine
Araw ng Kagitingan (April 9)
Religious traditions like the Feast of Our Lady of the Holy Rosary in Orani
Heritage tourism like Las Casas Filipinas de Acuzar
Cuisine

Traditional Cuisine of Bataan

Bataan’s cuisine reflects coastal and local flavors.

Popular foods include:

Buko pie
Tinapa (smoked fish)
Bibingka (rice cake)
Bagoong (fermented paste)
Festivals of Bataan

Bataan’s festivals celebrate history, culture, and nature.

Banga Festival (Balanga City)

Celebrated every April 28 (Feast of St. Joseph).
Features street dancing and cultural performances centered on the clay pot (banga).

Pawikan Festival (Morong)

Held in late November.
Promotes marine conservation and sea turtle protection.
Includes hatchling releases, clean-ups, and educational events.

Pagbubunyi Festival (Limay)

A cultural and religious festival reenacting the search for the Holy Cross.
Features colorful costumes and performances.

